Step 1 - Familiarize yourself with the data and the assignment

In this assignment you’ll do some exploratory data analysis with R on a dataset US census information based on the American Community Survey. The version of this data that we’ll be using is from a Kaggle dataset. See https://www.kaggle.com/muonneutrino/us-census-demographic-data/data and look at the column metadata for the county level table to see what the various columns mean.

As we did in class, you’ll be creating an R Markdown document to both prepare a dataset and do some analysis as well as to document the steps you did (and answer some questions I’ll throw at you).

You’ll notice a few “Hacker Extra” tasks thrown in. These are for those of you who want to go a little above and beyond and attempt some more challenging tasks. And, feel free to do a some free form Hacker Extra style work yourself - in other words, do something beyond what was asked. You’ll learn more.

Step 3 - Set working directory and explore data folder

Set the working directory or create an R Studio project in the current folder. You’ll notice that there is a folder named data. Inside of it you’ll find the data files for this assignment:

  • acs2015_census_tract_data.csv
  • acs2015_county_data.csv
  • us_census_bureau_regions_and_divisions.csv
  • county.csv
  • county_MI.csv

The first two files are from the Kaggle site for this dataset. The two files, county.csv and county_MI.csv, are files that I created. The first contains county level data from all states and the other just data from Michigan. The R script, census_data_prep.R was used to create these files and to merge information from the us_census_bureau_regions_and_divisions.csv file with the county data.

You might want to use shell commands or a text editor like Geany to snoop the files a bit.

Problem 2 - Basic plots for Income

Create a histogram, boxplot, kernel density plot and violin plot for median income for the entire US.

Write a short paragraph describing the distribution of median incomes.

From the Histogram as we can see that both the Median and the Mean incomes are equal and hence the distribution of income over the entire US is symmetrically distributed.

From the Boxplot, it can be said that, the Median Income for the entire US is closer to the lower end of the spectrum of all the values and is closer to the end of the left whiskers (down whiskers) than to that of the end of the right whisker (top whiskers). The Median income for the entire US is along the mid line of the box, starting a little below 50,000 and we can approximate the same as around $ 45,000.

From both the Kernel Density Plot as well as the Violin plot we can see that the spread of the Income for the entire US is topping and buldging respectively somehwere around 45,000.

Problem 4 - How do Michigan’s peninsulas compare?

Create a grouped box plot showing Income by peninsula. Make sure your graph has a title and good axis labels.

ggplot(county_MI, aes(x=peninsula, y=Income, color=peninsula)) + geom_boxplot() + labs(

  )

Do the peninsulas differ with respect to distribution of median income over the counties?

Yes, from the Boxplot as shown above, it looks like there is a significant difference in the distribution of median income in the peninsulas over the counties.

Create several more boxplots showing how the peninsulas compare with respect to some of the other variables. Summarize your findings in a few short paragraphs.

i) Population Distribution Across Peninsula

The total population distribution for LP is higher than that of the UP. The Median of the Total Population distribution for Upper Peninsula is closer to the lower end of the spectrum for all of the population value and is closer to the end of the left whiskers (down whiskers) than to that of the end of the right whisker (top whiskers), indicating thin population distribution in Upper Peninsula as compared to that of the Lower Peninsula. On the other hand, the Median of the Total Population distribution is higher in Lower Peninsula as compared to that of the Upper Peninsula.

ggplot(county_MI, aes(x=peninsula, y=TotalPop, fill=peninsula)) + geom_boxplot() + labs(
    x = "Peninsula",                                    # x axis title
    y = "Total Population",                             # y axis title
    title = "Population Distribution by Peninsula"      # main title of figure 
) + scale_y_log10()

ii) Poverty Distribution across Peninsula

The Median of the poverty distribution for the UP is somewhere around 16 and is closer to the end of the left whiskers (down whiskers) than to that of the end of the right whisker (top whiskers), indicating that the Median of the Poverty distribution is closer to the lower end of the entire spectrum in Upper Peninsula as compared to that of the Lower Peninsula. In case of the LP or Lower Peninsula, the Median of the poverty distribution is around 18 and is towards the right whiskers (top whiskers) as compared to the left whiskers (down whiskers). The Median of the poverty distribution for Lower Peninsula is at a higher side as compared to that of the Upper Peninsula.

ggplot(county_MI, aes(x=peninsula, y=Poverty, fill = peninsula)) + geom_boxplot() + labs(

The Median of the Child Poverty Distribution for Lower Peninsula is slightly below 25 and the Median of the Child Poverty Distribution for the entire spectrum of the boxplot is towards the top whiskers (or the right whiskers).

The widely varying values make this difficult to interpret in terms of looking for patterns. So, figure out a way to either change the axis scales or the plotted data itself to use a base 10 logarithmic scale (or transform).

# Scaled Plot of Total Population by Income
ggplot(data = county_df, aes(x = Income, y = TotalPop)) + geom_point() + scale_y_log10() 
## Warning: Removed 1 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

Write a short paragraph on why one might want to use a log scale or log transform of data when plotting.

The datasets might have values that vary from each other on a large scale as seen in the first scatterplot (# Plot of Total Population by Income, Not Scaled) above between Total Population and the Income. It is very hard to get a clarity on the data points whereby the datasets are overlapping on one another making it hard to comprehend any relationship between these two variables. This property of variability between two variables of data is due to the uneven variation of values with the mean value in the datasets often known as heteroscedastic variance. Using a log scale or, equivalently, using the log transform ‘fixes’ the uneven variability and gives a scale that is unbounded on both ends.

Also, for time-series data, the ability of a log scale to make fractional changes is immensely powerful. With log scale a constant percentage change is seen as a constant vertical distance so a constant growth rate is seen as a straight line. That is often a substantial advantage.

Another reason when log scale proves to be powerful, when it makes more realistic to represent the data in a reciprocal manner, as for example in research areas where someone is dealing with minutely small numbers.
